Create label for resized Images of dogs and cats¶

Cat --> 0

Dog --> 1

In [6]:
# Define the folder path
folder = r"D:\Deep Learning Data\dogs-vs-cats\train_resized"

# Get filenames
filenames = os.listdir(folder)

# Create labels list
labels = []

# Loop through filenames and assign labels
for i in range(len(filenames)):  # Loop through all images
    file_name = filenames[i]
    label = file_name[:3]  # Extract first three characters to identify 'dog' or 'cat'
    
    if label == 'dog':
        labels.append(1)
    else:
        labels.append(0)

Building the Neural Network¶

In [25]:
import tensorflow as tf
import tensorflow_hub as hub
import numpy as np  # Ensure numpy is imported

# Load MobileNetV2 from TensorFlow Hub
mobilenet_model = 'https://tfhub.dev/google/tf2-preview/mobilenet_v2/feature_vector/4'

# Wrap in Lambda layer to resolve Sequential model issues
pretrained_model = tf.keras.layers.Lambda(lambda x: hub.KerasLayer(mobilenet_model, trainable=False)(x), 
                                          input_shape=(224, 224, 3))

# Define the model
num_classes = 2
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    pretrained_model,
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
])

# Compile the model
model.compile(
    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0005),
    loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

# Print model summary
model.summary()

# Generate example data
X_train_scaled = np.random.rand(100, 224, 224, 3)
Y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, 100)
X_test_scaled = np.random.rand(50, 224, 224, 3)
Y_test = np.random.randint(0, 2, 50)

# Train the model
history = model.fit(
    X_train_scaled, Y_train,

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.applications import MobileNetV2
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, BatchNormalization, Input, GlobalAveragePooling2D
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

# Define the number of classes (adjust based on your task)
num_classes = 2

# Define the input layer
inputs = Input(shape=(224, 224, 3))

# Load MobileNetV2 from tf.keras.applications
base_model = MobileNetV2(input_shape=(224, 224, 3), include_top=False, weights='imagenet')
base_model.trainable = False  # Freeze the pre-trained weights

# Pass the inputs through the base model
x = base_model(inputs)

# Add global average pooling to reduce spatial dimensions
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)

# Add custom dense layers with regularization
x = Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = Dropout(0.3)(x)

# Output layer
outputs = Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')(x)

# Create the model
model = Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

# Compile the model
model.compile(
    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
    loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',  # Use 'categorical_crossentropy' if labels are one-hot encoded
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

# Display the model summary
model.summary()

from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, GlobalAveragePooling2D, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau, ModelCheckpoint

# Enable mixed precision training (reduces training time)
tf.keras.mixed_precision.set_global_policy('mixed_float16')

# Load MobileNetV2 with pretrained weights and freeze base layers
base_model = MobileNetV2(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))
base_model.trainable = False  # Freeze base model layers

# Add classification layers on top
x = base_model.output
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)  # Efficient pooling
x = Dropout(0.3)(x)  # Regularization to reduce overfitting
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.3)(x)
output = Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', dtype='float32')(x)  # Explicit dtype for stability

# Compile model
model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=output)
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-4), loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Preprocess the data using MobileNetV2's preprocessing function
X_train_scaled = tf.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input(X_train)
X_test_scaled = tf.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input(X_test)

# Efficient data augmentation pipeline
data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
    tf.keras.layers.RandomRotation(0.1)
])

# Create tf.data datasets with optimizations
BATCH_SIZE = 128  # Increased batch size for efficiency
AUTOTUNE = tf.data.AUTOTUNE

train_dataset = (
    tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train_scaled, y_train))
    .shuffle(1000)
    .batch(BATCH_SIZE)
    .map(lambda x, y: (data_augmentation(x), y), num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE)
    .prefetch(AUTOTUNE)
)

validation_dataset = (
    tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_test_scaled, y_test))
    .batch(BATCH_SIZE)
    .prefetch(AUTOTUNE)
)

# Define callbacks
callbacks = [
    EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True),
    ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.2, patience=3, min_lr=1e-6),
    ModelCheckpoint('best_model.h5', monitor='val_accuracy', save_best_only=True)
]

# Train model with fewer epochs for efficiency
history = model.fit(train_dataset, validation_data=validation_dataset, epochs=30, callbacks=callbacks)

# Evaluate the model
test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(validation_dataset)
print(f'Test Loss: {test_loss:.4f}')
print(f'Test Accuracy: {test_acc:.4f}')

# Function to plot training history
def plot_training_history(history):
    # Extract accuracy and loss values
    acc = history.history['accuracy']
    val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    
    epochs_range = range(len(acc))

    # Plot accuracy
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, acc, label='Training Accuracy', marker='o')
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_acc, label='Validation Accuracy', marker='o')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')

    # Plot loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label='Training Loss', marker='o')
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss', marker='o')
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')

    plt.show()

# Call the function to visualize the training history
plot_training_history(history)

from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import SGD
from tensorflow.keras.regularizers import l2

# Enable mixed precision training (reduces training time)
tf.keras.mixed_precision.set_global_policy('mixed_float16')

# Load MobileNetV2 with pretrained weights, freeze base layers initially
base_model = MobileNetV2(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))
base_model.trainable = False  # Freeze base model layers initially

# Add classification layers on top
x = base_model.output
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)  # Efficient pooling
x = Dropout(0.4)(x)  # Increased dropout for regularization
x = Dense(256, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(1e-4))(x)  # L2 Regularization
x = BatchNormalization()(x)  # Normalization to improve generalization
x = Dropout(0.4)(x)  # Additional dropout layer
output = Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax', dtype='float32')(x)  # Ensure float32 precision

# Compile the model (Phase 1: Train with Adam)
model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=output)
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-4), 
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', 
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Preprocess the data using MobileNetV2's preprocessing function
X_train_scaled = tf.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input(X_train)
X_test_scaled = tf.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input(X_test)

# Expanded data augmentation pipeline
data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
    tf.keras.layers.RandomRotation(0.15),
    tf.keras.layers.RandomContrast(0.2),
    tf.keras.layers.RandomTranslation(height_factor=0.1, width_factor=0.1),
    tf.keras.layers.RandomZoom(0.1),  # Added slight zoom for more variation
    tf.keras.layers.RandomBrightness(0.2)  # Added brightness variation
])

# Create tf.data datasets with optimizations
BATCH_SIZE = 128  # Increased batch size for efficiency
AUTOTUNE = tf.data.AUTOTUNE

train_dataset = (
    tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train_scaled, y_train))
    .shuffle(2000)
    .batch(BATCH_SIZE)
    .map(lambda x, y: (data_augmentation(x), y), num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE)
    .prefetch(AUTOTUNE)
)

validation_dataset = (
    tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_test_scaled, y_test))
    .batch(BATCH_SIZE)
    .prefetch(AUTOTUNE)
)

# Define callbacks
callbacks = [
    EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True),
    ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.2, patience=3, min_lr=1e-6),
    ModelCheckpoint('best_model.h5', monitor='val_accuracy', save_best_only=True)
]

# Train model with initial frozen base layers
history = model.fit(train_dataset, validation_data=validation_dataset, epochs=20, callbacks=callbacks)

# Fine-tuning: Unfreeze last few layers of base_model for better generalization
base_model.trainable = True
for layer in base_model.layers[:-30]:  # Keep first ~75% frozen, fine-tune last 30 layers
    layer.trainable = False

# Compile model again with SGD + Momentum for fine-tuning
model.compile(optimizer=SGD(learning_rate=1e-3, momentum=0.9, nesterov=True), 
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', 
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train again with fine-tuned layers
history_finetune = model.fit(train_dataset, validation_data=validation_dataset, epochs=10, callbacks=callbacks)

# Evaluate the final model
test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(validation_dataset)
print(f'Test Loss: {test_loss:.4f}')
print(f'Test Accuracy: {test_acc:.4f}')

# Function to plot training history
def plot_training_history(history):
    # Extract accuracy and loss values
    acc = history.history['accuracy']
    val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    
    epochs_range = range(len(acc))

    # Plot accuracy
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, acc, label='Training Accuracy', marker='o')
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_acc, label='Validation Accuracy', marker='o')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')

    # Plot loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label='Training Loss', marker='o')
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss', marker='o')
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')

    plt.show()

# Call the function to visualize the training history
plot_training_history(history)
